### 📌 Spring Boot Version — @Autowired on Constructor

```java
@Component
public class Student {

    private final String name;
    private final Address address;

    // @Autowired optional in Spring Boot 4.3+ if only one constructor
    @Autowired
    public Student(Address address) {
        this.name    = "Nivas";
        this.address = address;
    }

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
        address.show();
    }
}
```

---

### 📌 Lombok shortcut (used in real projects)

```java
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor   // generates constructor for all final fields
public class Student {

    private final Address address;  // auto-injected via constructor
    private final CourseService courseService;
}
```

> This is exactly how Spring Boot production code looks — `@RequiredArgsConstructor` + `final` fields = constructor injection with zero boilerplate.

---

### 📊 All 3 Injection Types — Side by Side

```java
// Field Injection
@Autowired
private Address address;

// Setter Injection
@Autowired
public void setAddress(Address address) {
    this.address = address;
}

// Constructor Injection ✅ (recommended)
@Autowired
public Student(Address address) {
    this.address = address;
}
```

| | Field | Setter | Constructor |
|---|---|---|---|
| `final` fields | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| Easy to unit test | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ |
| Mandatory deps | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| Optional deps | ❌ | ✅ | ❌ |
| Spring Boot recommended | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |

---

### 🔑 Interview One-Liner
> "Constructor Injection injects all mandatory dependencies at object creation time via the constructor — making fields immutable (`final`), ensuring the object is always in a valid state, and making unit testing easy without a Spring context."
